    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p>
                    <bibl><ptr target="#oliverioDAI2"/>, p. 112, n. <citedRange>88</citedRange>, fig. 44</bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>9.200</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl> Morelli in <ptr target="#SECir"/>, <citedRange>286</citedRange> (no image) as unpublished</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>024400</citedRange></bibl>.
                    Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#cdlBE"/>, <citedRange>1988.1011</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#dthorn-thorn2009"/>, p. <citedRange>140</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-64045"><name nymRef="#Ἠρίλοχος">Ἠρίλοχος</name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-63464"><name type="patronymic" nymRef="#Δᾶμις">Δάμιος</name></persName></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p><app loc="1"><lem>&gt;Ἠρίλοχος</lem>
                    <rdg resp="#SECir">Ἰφίλοχος</rdg> <note>Morelli's reading.</note>
                </app></p>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Erilokhos fils de Damis.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Erilochos son of Damis.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Erilochos figlio di Damis.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>The stele was given again as unpublished, without illustration and erroneously read, by Morelli as <bibl><ptr target="#SECir"/>, <citedRange>286</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
	             <p>The Torns' suggestion that the stele might come from the North Necropolis is based upon the idea that Italian excavations before World War II took place only 
	             in that Necropolis. However funerary inscriptions have often been found fortuitously.</p>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
    </text>
